Citation Diversity Tracking: Further analysis (Median split by Publication Year, Analyses by Journal Impact Factor)

  • authored by: Lioba Enk, Spokesperson for the Diversity and Inclusion Committee (MPI CBS, Leipzig, Germany)1
  • last updated: 11 August 2025


Reference


Steinfath, P. *, Azanova, M. *, Kapralov, N. *, Loesche, T., Enk, L., Nikulin, V. ° & Villringer, A. °. Heartbeat-evoked responses in M/EEG: A systematic review of methods with suggestions for analysis and reporting. Manuscript submitted for publication (2025-08).

Code sections (A) + (B) reported in :
Main text under ‘Statement on gender composition within HER research and citation diversity’
(Steinfath, Azanova, Kapralov et al., 2025)

Code sections (C) reported in :
Section D (Steinfath, Azanova, Kapralov et al., 2025)


Description


This script processes output from citation-diversity-tracking (v2.0), specifically for Steinfath, Azanova, Kapralov et al. (2025). The output can be found at /manuscript-results/2025_steinfath-et-al_hep-review.

Further analyses were conducted on the corpus of literature included to this systematic review. This was a new opportunity, to further describe development across the reviewed Heart-beat evoked reponses (HER) studies published over time. In the soon future, I hope to integrate these analyses into the main citation-diversity-tracking tool.

The input file for this code is an adapted citation-diversity-tracking output file, and can be found at manuscript-results/2025_steinfath-et-al_hep-review/ReviewLit:

  • ‘20250619_hep_review_trackcitingbehav_predictions_checked_FALAclustering_MedianSplitYear_EigenfactorGrouping.csv’

Note, some information was added manually to the input file (column labels):

  • PublicationMonth: Publication months across the references publsihed at median(PublicationYear), here 2020.
  • Eigenfactor_JCR_2024: extracted from the Web of Science’s Journal Citation Report data on 23 June 2025, if available.
  • Eigenfactor_JCR_PublicationYear: extracted from the Web of Science’s Journal Citation Report data on 23 June 2025, if available.
  • Dworkin_5_member: Top 5 Neuroscience Journals (across 1995-2018), that is Neuron, Nat Neurosci, J Neurosci, NeuroImage, Brain, extracted from Dworkin et al. (Nat Neurosci 2020).
    –> /data/configs/eigenfactor_dworkin_hefter_grouping.csv.
  • Hefter_50_member: Top 50 Neuroscience Journals (as of Sept 2023), extracted from ‘Supplementary Information for “Gender imbalance in citations most pronounced in high-impact neuroscience journals”’ (p. 15) of Hefter et al. (bioRxiv 2025).
    –> /data/configs/eigenfactor_dworkin_hefter_grouping.csv

This script computes (A) a median split by publication year to assess changes in approximated gender ratios (FF / MF / FM / MM) of authors, (B) clustering of author names in first and last authoring position, and (C) changes in those approximated gender proportions by Eigenfactor score (Bergstrom et al., 2008).

med = median(data$PublicationYear)
data$PublicationYear_mediansplit = ifelse(data$PublicationYear < med, 
                                          "below_median", "above_median")

(C) Overview : Top 50 Neuroscience Journals in Hefter et al. (2025)


We analysed approximated gender compositions across three Eigenfactor Score groupings.

  • Procedure 1: HER references published in ‘Dworkin-Top5’
  • Procedure 2: HER references published in ‘Hefter-Top50’
  • Procedure 3: HER references published in ‘Hefter-Top50’ & adding all HER references published in journals that had an Eigenfactor score (from the JCR 2024) higher than the lowest one included in Hefter et al., that is an Eigenfactor score of 0.016.
  • Remaining HER references

Importantly, we made two further decisions: (1) Three journals included in Hefter et al. (2025) were now below Hefter et al.’s lowest score2 - we decided to yet include them to Procedure 2; (2) Four journals in which HER research was published did not have Eigenfactor scores when we checked (JCR 2024) - we decided to include them to Procedure 3.

Decision (1)

Decision (2)

Create grouping variable…

data = data %>%
  mutate(
    eigenfactor_grouping = case_when(Dworkin_5_member == "Y" ~ "Procedure1",
                                     Hefter_50_member == "Y" ~ "Procedure2",
                                     (Eigenfactor_JCR2024_above_lowest_Hefter_Cutoff_0.016 == "Y" | 
                                        taken_as_above2024cutoff_because_HefterMember == "Y" | 
                                        taken_as_above2024cutoff_because_NA == "Y") ~ "Procedure3",
                                     (Eigenfactor_JCR2024_above_lowest_Hefter_Cutoff_0.016 == "N" &
                                       Hefter_50_member != "Y") ~ "Remaining"))


Procedure 1


procedure1_count = nrow(data[data$eigenfactor_grouping == "Procedure1",])
data[data$eigenfactor_grouping == "Procedure1",] %>%
  group_by(GendCat_posthoc) %>%
  summarise(count = n(),
            total_count = procedure1_count,
            your_percent = n() / procedure1_count * 100)
